  "topic_name": "Earth and Solar System",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "The Sun is a star at the center of our solar system, providing light and heat to Earth. Earth rotates on its axis once every 24 hours, causing day and night. Earth revolves around the Sun in about 365 days (one year), causing seasons due to Earth's tilted axis. The Moon is Earth's natural satellite, revolving around Earth in about 28 days. The Moon reflects sunlight and shows different phases: new moon, crescent, half moon, gibbous, and full moon. Our solar system has 8 planets in order from the Sun: Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. Stars are distant suns, and constellations are patterns formed by groups of stars.",
